[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Considering test adjustments**\n\nI’m pondering if a tight loop might cause the background future to wait for non-empty `client.requests`, while `sendFetches()` keeps adding requests when there's no poll. This could stack OOM in the main at `sendFetches`, possibly due to a huge `subscriptionState`. It's possible that repeated fetched records inflate `completedFetches`. If the future can't run, that would lead to ongoing fetches. I think the simplest approach might be adjusting the existing test to skip the heavy upstream test under normal conditions.\n\n**Evaluating test failures**\n\nI’m seeing that all external tests are failing, so I need to consider my options. One idea is to use JUnit tags to exclude certain tests, but given the failure trace is from an existing test, it might mean the addition changed something in the order or memory. I could also increase the test JVM maxHeapSize in build.gradle to see if that helps the situation. Maybe with a larger heap, the 400 fetches test will complete successfully.\n\n**Considering support changes**\n\nI’m thinking about a support change related to testing reliability. It seems crucial not to skip any tests. I wonder if I could mark the Fetcher test with @Timeout as non-preemptive. Maybe there's an Out of Memory (OOM) issue because of preemptive execution? I need to check if the existing @Timeout runs on a separate thread or not. Actually, JUnit @Timeout defaults to the same thread unless the configuration for junit.jupiter.execution.timeout.mode is adjusted. Time to review the properties!", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_01259a6406a45dc5016a0f500c76fc819e8ed66f0100b85788\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqD1AiUete6g2Tzim31iXz1NNbQFF86rnUziR5R4-sYUqvnKej2GvV7xe0maIX96nW9vQD2dQIvSVhIei5YXZR3PUvA54mjSt0230ULSq66HwqjyZYRSB-PRpV8vYe0nuq43FoUpZIEGgjyML35CBQ7VmGWEPwpJWzq3r-PG-zp9JOhEv6tcF3LrUS